<section class="content-center">
  <h3>In Retrospect...</h3>
  <p>...this was an extremely eye opening process for me. Like I mentioned before this was the first full-stack application project I had ever worked on. I learned the value that comes from creating a design blueprint beforehand. Without our preplanning and organization of our features, we would not have even come close to a finished product.</p>
  <h4>Design Retrospective</h4>
  <p><b>From a purely design aspect,</b> I realized that design is not only limited to graphics and UIs, rather it encompasses everything under the umbrella of user experience. We had a goal to create a user experience where users could have meaningfull conversations with their friends without having to put too much effort into curating an authentic message. While this experience is not visual, we still had to design features that would allow the users to experience the feeling we wanted them to. Designing our hugs, keep in touch, and streaks features was more like solving a puzzle to trick the human brain, as opposed to creating a UI with graphics that looked cool. This project fully changed my understanding of what it means to be a designer.</p>
  <p>I think that if I were to change anything, I would have done more to create a design system/UI kit before actually having our team design the individual screens and features. In our project we kind of just went ahead with designing each screen, giving us some obvious design conflicts and mismatches. We also struggled with keeping our component sizing consistent across different devices, which was an obstacle we didn't pay much attention to until we absolutely had to. A big mistake on our part that took a ton of time to remedy</p>
  <h4>Technical Retrospective</h4>
  <p>It's hard to say that I would change our tools for frontend development, since I had very little experience at the time working with mobile frontend applications, but I can say for sure that trying to build a cross platform application is not easy stuff. Furthermore trying to work with expo and React Native was something of a nightmare. <b>However,</b> through this process I was able to see a lot of patterns in how frontend systems work, and I was able to abstract a lot of those patterns myself by the end of our project. If I were to go back and recode with the knowledge I have now, our application would be far more efficient, organized, and robust.</p>
  <p>So yeah, since I learned so much the first time around, I wouldn't have changed the way we went about the technical development of our project. Now, if I were to go and rebuild this application right now, I would definitely change many things.</p> 
  <p>For starters I would make this application either web based, or android only. I think react is a nice tool, but the React Native development environment is not yet suited to really be a solid candidate for mobile development in terms of developer expereince. I also think that using React Native kept me from learning a lot of the ins and outs of mobile development. Instead it just shoved a layer of tag based abstraction over the mobile environment.</p>
</section>
